oldwasser", "start": "1536.264","u": "Yes."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1537.152","u": "So. Tell me, please, did the Maquis have any poems, any songs?"},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1542.929","u": "Yes, they created very beautiful songs."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1545.049","u": "Would you perhaps sing one for me?"},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1547.904","u": "[chuckle] [unintelligible] I can&#39;t sing. I have no voice."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1550.886","u": "You may do it in a very low voice. The important thing is that the words be clear. Right?"},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1556.621","u": "Yes."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1558.683","u": "Just hum it, so to speak. Try, please."},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1561.314","u": "I cannot remember."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1562.864","u": "Try, please. Let us see."},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1564.702","u": "[In French] [unintelligible]? [sings] Friends, you heard the glory of liberty, which has called you. Come to the ranks [unintelligible] stretch out your hand to your brothers, who agree with you [feel like you] [unintelligible; &#34;to fight against&#34;?] be it those who abandoned the legions [ranks] be it those who abandoned the nations. Friends, you hear the glory which is calling you. On the hills is liberty, which will unite you, comrades, Jews, Italians [unintelligible]."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1565.612","u": "[In German] Yes. Do you know any Jewish songs from the lagers?"},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1570.861","u": "From the lagers? Yes."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1572.077","u": "Yes. Will you please sing one for me?"},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1574.296","u": "But I myself was not in the lager. These are songs which we have had come to us [?]."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1577.212","u": "Yes. Will you sing one?"},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1579.023","u": "[recites] &#34;[The first line is not clear] Ravensbr&#195;ck, Ravensbr&#195;ck, you are in the abyss [?]. And perhaps one day we will see freedom. Then we shall say to life once again, yes, Ravensbr&#195;ck, you are the past, the sorrow, the destruction, by the Germans, by the Nazis, of the Jewish people. We the young have faith in life [?]. One must strive to live. But the Germans have besmirched this striving with black ink.&#34; There are some more words, but I do not remember them."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1616.139","u": "Recite please in French."},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1618.964","u": "[She recites another song in French.]"},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1651.679","u": "[In German] There are some more words to this too, but I do not remember them."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1662.701","u": "Well, tell me, what do you think in general? What will become of the future?"},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1668.508","u": "About the future?"},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1669.537","u": "[adjusts the equipment]"},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1670.856","u": ". . . when one is able to talk about the future it is [appears] very beautiful. But we cannot imagine at all what the future will look like. The Polish Jews had been very much oppressed. They have absolutely no &#34;moral instinct.&#34; They have absolutely no . . . no hope to live. They want to wander. They want to run. To Palestine, unfortunately, they are not admitted. England does not want to give any certificates. To America one is unable [to go]. People have affidavits, but the quota is blocked. Well, what should the Jews do? Where should they go? They have no homeland. They want to have a national homeland. They want to be Palestinian citizens. And why should we not be? And so, unfortunately, no . . . I cannot imagine at all how life . . . the problem of the Jewish life in general, all over the world, will . . . will not take shape. It is a question. We are at the start of a world conference. Perhaps they will talk about us, too. Who knows? The Jews in general . . . a European Jew is not . . . is not too well at the moment. I mean morally. He has no homeland. He has no, as one says in Yiddish, roof over his head. And what can he do? He is broken up. No family. And out of a family, out of the most beautiful families, not a single person was left. And out of many hundreds and millions not even one has remained. What can one . . ."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1778.096","u": "For which paper do you work, here in Paris?"},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1783.237","u": "I? For the Neue . . . Neue Presse. This is a paper which naturally defends the working class."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1792.307","u": "Aha. How many . . . how many Jewish papers are there in Paris?"},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1798.060","u": "There are many Jewish papers, but not all . . . not all of the same opinion. There are Zionist papers. There are socialist, so-called Bundist [an old, Jewish socialist party founded in Czarist Russia] papers. They are the worst, because they are against . . . against the progressive labor movement."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1817.803","u": "The Bundist papers?"},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1819.419","u": "[They] take always the stand . . ."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1821.190","u": "Yes?"},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1821.742","u": "The Bundist paper always takes the opposite stand, against the Neue Presse. This is a struggle between two camps of labor."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1831.682","u": "Is the Bundist press not a socialist press, not a Social-Democratic press?"},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1836.210","u": "A Social-Democratic [paper] as it is said, but in reality they are not the way the worker wants to have it."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1845.394","u": "You think so?"},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1846.372","u": "That is what I think."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1848.374","u": "But there are many people who read this paper. Isn&#39;t that so?"},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1851.948","u": "There are, but it does not have too much of a success [following] I am not talking now as a follower of the Neue Presse . . ."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1858.151","u": "Yes?"},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1858.533","u": ". . . which has a tremendous success."},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1861.831","u": "[In Yiddish] When one comes to a Jewish home, in every Jewish family, in the morning one sees a Jewish newspaper."},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1868.912","u": "[In German] This is the Neue Presse, naturally. As one sees a French newspaper, a working man&#39;s paper, or any other one, but the . . . but the Jew, he reads the . . . the Neue Presse."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1883.101","u": "The Neue Presse."},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1883.877","u": "Because in it he has . . ."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1884.293","u": "Is the Neue Presse Zionistic?"},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1886.707","u": "The Neue Presse is not Zionistic. The Neue Presse is a . . . not communistic, but it defends the Jewish immigrant, defends the Jewish [unintelligible] man, the worker who works at home, who works in the factories, and the intellectuals who . . ."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1906.619","u": "What does it say about Palestine?"},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1908.611","u": "About Palestine? What does it say about Palestine?"},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1912.762","u": "Yes."},    {"who": "Bertha Goldwasser", "start": "1913.499","u": "They have a very strong [?] opinion about Palestine. They help in Palestine the Jews who organize in Palestine against the . . . against the bourgeois camp [class] who want to create their own homeland, who want something too . . ."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1936.562","u": "I thank you very much, Mrs. Goldwasser. This is a very good . . . [mid-sentence interruption of interview apparently due to the end of the spool]"}        ]
